	abstract = {The sociology of collective action has addressed one-sided, nongovernmental anti-minority violence rather infrequently. To explain the preconditions for violence, the "power approach of intergroup hostility" is drawn upon, which entails two processes: the red or imagined threat by an out-group and the identification with an in-group. The conflict dynamic arises out of a change in the balance of power between groups (immigration, economic success, equal rights, symbolic threats). This change has to be translated into a threatening scenario by (mass) communication in which norms change and the target group is gradually delegitimized and "excommunicated" so that violence tends to be regarded as a means of "social control" and as self-help by a group. The "power approach" has to be supplemented with the concept of "frame analysis" and with the theory of social control developed by Donald Black in order to explain the use of pogrom-like violence. Pogroms are defined as entailing three partners: a group of the majority, a targeted minority, and the state. The aggressor regards himself as the legitimate representative of the majority. Pogroms require a specific "opportunity structure" in order to develop in which the behavior of the government, police, public opinion and the bystanders fulfil a key function in the escalation of violence. The excessive violence of pogroms does nor fit easily into the categories of purposeful or symbolic action. Violent actions and potential effects seem to be inseparably linked in such a way that the more violence employed by the mob, the better it can expel, deprave and humiliate its victims.},
