	volume = {26},
	issn = {0049-1225},
	abstract = {Observing the processes of political and economic transformation after 1989 it turns out that youth and representatives of the youth's movements are annually more and more pushed out from the social happenings, their subject position marginalizes. Youth is seen by the eyes of public as a problematic and dangerous social group subjected to all traps of the open society. The representatives lose the partnership towards the state step by step, even in the case of keeping and increasing the property of the former youth organization instead of bringing benefits for children and youth of the Slovak Republic. In our opinion, the marginalization problem lays in our totalitarian, brown and red traditions. The system of work with young people, according to one party's aims, reached the high level of ideological unification and political action of youth. This became a tradition influencing the experience and minds of many generations. As a part of this, the young generation was pictured in the public opinion and youth's self-reflection as a historically important subject with a social mission. From this point of view, the contemporaneous problem is not the youth's ”marginalization”, but rather our traditionalism. The modernization is the process of social changes. Sometimes it affects very painfully our traditional waiting for a collectivistic revolutionary behavior of the young generation's movement. The problem of stated social appeal is expected to be sorted out as in the past (e.g. collectivization, urbanization and industrialization, etc.). A substance of the systematic change causes the modern waiting. It tends to combine a modern prosperity of the society with perfect and enormous individual's efforts at the competitive labor market. Youth changes from the homogenous social group (as it was stated in the socialistic social structure) to social-age aggregate of individuals in the certain period of a life circle. A significant change of the original youth's identity is connected with the highest authorities inability to understand this change in the Postsocialistic countries. As well as to accept the fact that the state secure at least appropriate and timely legislative, support financially an elementary infrastructure of the work with youth based on civil youth associations, and secure the stability of the process of socialization. (Merkel, A., 1994). The challenge of the modernization growing from the transformation processes is not delimited only to the young generation. Also other age groups feel to be spoken to. Consequently, this also marginalizes the young generation. This challenge is the challenge for an individual and determined as an individualization. Ken Roberts (1994) states it as a personal disposition or young adolescents ability to take on a responsibility for their decisions as well as admit the risks and social impacts thereof. According to Ivan Velev (1994) individualization is the presumption for the modernization, German sociologists extrapolate it also at the reconstruction of the former totalitarian society in the GDR. For these reasons we consider the transformation of organized youth's movements, changes in position of the civil youth associations, representatives conduct towards the state and youth itself to be a very remarkable sociological phenomenon with its theoretical and pragmatic implications for the processes of modernization. As for active social actors, in accordance to Alain Touraine, it is incontestable that the individuals - actors who seek to achieve personal goals in an environment made up of other agents”...and constituting a community to which they feel they belong and whose culture and rules of institutional functioning they share, at least in part”. (Touraine, A. 1993, p. 425). To produce the active social actors, the existence of certain personal aims is not sufficient. Also an ability to communicate and manifest an engaged citizenship is needed. The representatives of the youth associations were able to unify themselves and manifest their engagement to secure financial and organizational programs of leisure time activities for children and youth from the budget. They cooperated also in the effort to obtain certain possibility to participate at administrative bodies as use more effectively the youth property. The gradual process of the political system transformation is reflected visibly above all in the pluralization of the youth's movement. There is disability and strong disinterest from the representatives to articulate specific interests and needs of the young people in the field of education, professional preparation, social and housing policies. The participation at the social modernization impacts is expected only from the left youth's organizations or special humanity and charity organizations. Interests and needs of youth are more and more distant from the representatives who lose the ability to reflect new processes into meaningful program so that public and youth will accept them as real problems. Generally we can state that during the past period no demands presented by the Slovak Council of Youth (SCY) in the public as youth's interests and needs were supported by civil participation of youth (i.e., petition, recessive demonstration). Furthermore, we do not know the case of SCY applying for the support of those whose interests it represents. This is the specific situation distinguished by A. Touraine in Chile. The admitted representatives of youth into the state administrative bodies and developed communication between state and associations representatives can not supple the sense of the citizenship. According to an author, it is very remarkable that”...while there is such a massive demand everywhere for political participation and dialogue, there is still little capacity for collective action and the ideological formulation of such demands”. (Touraine, A., 1993, p. 426). Moreover, the main aim of the social actors is according to A. Touraine to encourage ”the spirit of the citizenship” in the frame of the youth policy. According to Dieter Rucht (Rucht, D., 1994) it is not enough to create problems of a certain arrangement by the deprivation of individuals and/or by artificial conviction of something wrong with them. The change can be reached by the different institutional arrangement of interests' satisfaction or innovation of the laws. This assumes scandalize opponents occasionally, create intellectual conceptions and strategic programs inspiring the expectations of success, help to make specific conditions also for the mobilization and time stability of the civil movement. The Council of Youth is a collective actor. If support absents, young citizens are not protected from the increasing marginalization or social isolation resulted from subordinated education and youth policies to the market economy or ideology. This explains why do the subjects of the European Council give an attention to the problem of associative youth life. Beside this, the research-analytical effort and methodologies to understand the development of the youth's movement in the Middle European countries seem to be sometimes a type of sociological intervention. They focus to cause expected modernization changes. Experts of the European Council (Stafseng, O., 1994) evaluated positively the certain period of the transformation process according to associative life of youth with the dominant status of plurality in the political system. The challenge for the modernization of Slovakia and to join the structure of Europe is also the challenge for the Slovak Council of Youth to be a collective actor, admit its mission, encourage the ”citizenship” feeling of the young people, and create conditions for articulation and solution of their problems and needs.},
	number = {4},
	journal = {SOCIOLOGIA},
	author = {MACHACEK, L.},
	year = {1994},
	pmid = {WOS:A1994QG72500005},
	keywords = {COLLECTIVE ACTOR, THE CHALLENGE OF THE MODERNIZATION, YOUTH MOVEMENT},
